      <hedline>
        <hl1>Aging in America: The Path Ahead</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dr Pankaj Gupta letter on Peter G Peterson's Sept 18 Op-Ed on outlook for Medicare reform</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Our Graying Budget Priorities,'' by Peter G. Peterson (Op-Ed, Sept. 18):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Our Graying Budget Priorities,'' by Peter G. Peterson (Op-Ed, Sept. 18):</p>
        <p>Regarding Medicare, Mr. Peterson says ''reform will involve painful moral as well as political decisions,'' and he asks, ''How will we decide who gets what health care?'' In fact, the consumer must decide before our politicians decide for us. Just what are the priorities of the consumers of health care -- the American people?</p>
        <p>As a country, is it to boast an advanced level of expensive medical diagnostics involving an insurmountable amount of insurance paperwork in a litigious society in which defensive medicine is practiced? Or is it to provide appropriate, evidence-based medicine affordable to a larger population of Americans?</p>
        <p>PANKAJ GUPTA, M.D.  Framingham, Mass., Sept. 18, 2000</p>
      </block>
